<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   A great night for beetles fans
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
those who have video recorders. The Grass Roots Tiger (8.30 C4) tells of
cicindela campestris, the tiger beetle, a green chap, about an inch long,
who will eat any other insect, even one twice his size. Summer Wildlife, on
the other hand, screened simultaneously on BBC2, is concerned with
coccinellidae, or the ladybird, whose diet is highly specialised: she sticks
to aphids. The excellent series TV Heroes moves on to Barbara Woodhouse who
might be better described as a heroine than a hero, and regarded by most as
an eccentric rather than a heroine. Undeniably memorable, however: who can
ever forget 'SiTT]' (8.50 BBC1). You can see why the judiciary loathes
television programmes specialising in miscarriages of justice: there is now
a long list of cases where television programmes have led to people being
released from prison, showing that police and judges were wrong. In Trial
And Error David Jessel takes up the case of Mark Cleary who was convicted of
the murder of a boy in Nottingham in 1985 (9.00 C4).
</TEXT>
