<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 93 / Steaming into Bristol
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BULK carrier Pytchley yesterday became the largest ship to enter
Bristol's Royal Portbury dock when it delivered 37,000 tonnes of coal to
National Power, the electricity generator, at the company's new import
facility.
The facility, built at a cost of Pounds 80m, is likely to handle much less
than its 7m tonnes capacity this year. The government's decision to
subsidise output from at least a dozen British pits means that National
Power will import only about 1m tonnes this year and a similar amount next
year. But the company says the facility has already paid for itself by
forcing British Coal to reduce its prices in five-year contracts.
The port will also be used to import cars and commodities such as timber and
agricultural products. Unloading can take place at 4,000 tonnes an hour
compared with a previous rate of 4,000 tonnes a day.
</TEXT>
