<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 93 / Post Office chief demands sell-off decision
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON, Industrial Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CHAIRMAN of the Post Office, Mr Michael Heron, yesterday renewed calls
for a government decision on the company's privatisation.
A decision had been expected by the end of this month but the issue, which
has been dogged by controversy, is likely to be delayed by the illness of Mr
Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, who suffered a heart attack
this week.
It was already delayed by the sacking in last month's government reshuffle
of Mr Edward Leigh, who was junior trade and industry minister.
Mr Heron said recent signals from the government threw 'very little light'
on whether privatisation would go ahead. 'When you're running a business,
the one thing that gets you is uncertainty,' he said.
As on previous occasions, Mr Heron refused to be drawn on his views on
privatisation. 'What we need is the freedom to meet the commercial
challenges of the future, which lie in technology and internationally,' he
said. 'Whether that means privatisation is for the government to judge.' He
was now hoping for a decision by the end of the year. 'If it goes beyond
that point, all you're doing is increasing the hill we've got to climb in
terms of opportunities and challenges,' he said.
Mr Heron said the board would prefer the businesses to be kept together if
privatised. He denied that morale in the Post Office was low as a result of
the delay. Although morale had suffered slightly, he said, it was still
higher than in most commercial organisations.
Mr Heron was presenting the Post Office's results for the year 1992-93.
Pre-tax profits were up 15 per cent at a record Pounds 283m - the 17th
successive year of unsubsidised profits.
The Post Office contributed Pounds 80m in cash to the Treasury over the
year, compared with a targeted contribution of Pounds 66m. Mr Heron
described the sharp rise to Pounds 181m required by the Treasury this year
as 'a daunting challenge'. He said the board was examining ways to raise the
money, and did not rule out higher letter prices, which have been frozen
since September 1991.
Profits from Royal Mail were down 5 per cent at Pounds 252m. Those at Post
Office Counters, the retail network, were down 4 per cent at Pounds 25m.
Losses at Parcelforce, the parcel delivery business, were reduced from
Pounds 24m to Pounds 13m. Postal workers in London are to vote on strike
action over compensation payments for compulsory transfer of staff between
sorting offices. The Union of Communications Workers said nearly 6,000 jobs
were due to be cut in London over the next three years because of the
introduction of new machinery.
</TEXT>
