<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Fowler attacks Polly administrator
over party cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR NORMAN Fowler, the Conservative party chairman, last night attacked
Touche Ross, the Polly Peck administrator, for taking 18 months to reply to
the party's letter giving details of donations received from companies
associated with Mr Asil Nadir, the fugitive businessman.
As the government rejected a Labour assault on 'sleaze and corruption' in
the party's funding, Sir Norman hoped the accountants would now 'start
dealing with us and will not seek to pursue this through the newspapers.'
The party confirmed last night Touche had asked for the return of the Pounds
440,000 donated by Mr Nadir's companies, but said the approach contained no
evidence the funds had been stolen.
The party is to consult its lawyers before replying. It has pledged to
return the money if it can be proved it has been stolen.
This latest twist to the saga came as the Tories maintained in the Commons
that financial support for political parties should be left on a voluntary
basis and not made a compulsory burden on the taxpayer.
Mr David Hunt, employment secretary, told MPs that Labour's hidden agenda in
the row over Conservative finances was to get its 'paws' on the public purse
by forcing the introduction of state funding for political parties. Labour's
financial 'crisis' had left it eager for the taxpayer to 'bail out their
sinking ship', he said.
Both Mr Hunt and Sir Norman attacked Mrs Margaret Beckett, the Labour party
deputy leader, for choosing to lace her opening speech with 'rumour' and
'innuendo'. It was a 'shabby, irresponsible, miserable' speech of which he
thought Mrs Beckett would one day be ashamed, Mr Hunt said.
Mrs Beckett repeatedly sparked pandemonium on the Tory backbenches with the
forthrightness of her allusions to recent reports about the alleged trading
of contributions for honours and the extent to which the Conservative party
is funded by undisclosed or foreign donations.
For as long as the Conservative party would not reveal where it got 'more
than 50 per cent' of its money from, Mrs Beckett said, the suspicion would
exist that the damage that would be done if voters found out must be 'even
worse' than the damage being in-flicted at the moment.
While Mr Hunt attacked Labour's links with the trade unions, Mrs Beckett
maintained that the 'heart of the matter' was that a wide range of
allegations could be made because of the 'secrecy' that surrounded Tory
party accounts.
She said that the Hartley Investment Trust - the company which had given the
largest ever recorded donation to the Conservative party - had broken the
law by twice failing to file its annual accounts on time. Sir Marcus Fox,
chairman of the powerful Tory 1922 committee of Tory backbench MPs, was a
director of the company, she said.
After the debate ended amid a noisy storm of accusations and
counter-accusations, a Labour motion expressing concern at Mr Nadir's
donations and urging the government to begin proceedings against companies
making undeclared political donations was defeated by 291 votes to 250, a
government majority of 41.
</TEXT>
