<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Tebbit warns on Maastricht bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD Tebbit, the former Conservative cabinet minister and party chairman,
aligned himself with Mr Tony Benn,MP for Chesterfield and champion of
Labour's left wing, in opposing the Maastricht bill in the House of Lords
last night.
He also ruffled ministerial feathers by challenging an agreement between
government and opposition leaders on the time to be devoted to a debate on a
common European defence policy.
Baroness Thatcher, the former prime minister, opted for a non-speaking role
as Lord Tebbit initially took the lead in attacking the bill from the
government back benches.
He stressed that he was at one with Mr Benn in resisting the federalist
tendencies of the European Community so as to ensure that basic decisions
affecting the British people were taken at Westminster and not Brussels.
Lord Tebbit then upset ministers by making an unsuccessful attempt to
prolong the discussion on a common defence policy on the grounds that
Baroness Chalker, foreign office minister, had failed to deal with all the
issues in making what was intended to be the final speech.
With no guillotine available to the government in the Lords arrangements for
an informal timetable assume special significance, particularly at the start
of a marathon committee stage - 430 amendments are already down for
discussion and more are expected.
Lady Chalker commented 'I do not think anything I say in this debate will
ever satisfy Lord Tebbit'.
In the first voting challenge - on an amendment moved by Lord Jay (Lab)
seeking to overturn the provision in the treaty imposing European
citizenship on British nationals - the government secured a majority of 194
(242-48).
Lord Tebbit forecast that, in spite of ministerial assurances that European
citizenship would confer new rights and no new responsibilities, British
nationals were likely to be subject to new demands, possibly including
conscription to the armed forces,as federalism gained momentum in the years
ahead.
</TEXT>
