<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 93 / Financial crisis hits biggest rail union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RMT transport union, which represents 105,000 workers mainly in the rail
and maritime sectors, faces a financial crisis.
The union spent Pounds 3.6m more than its Pounds 6.4m income in 1991, the
last year for which it has provided figures.
The crisis is likely to be exacerbated by a significant cut in income from
its core membership in British Rail. Officials say it could face a cut of
more than Pounds 1m in income following BR's decision to stop 'check-off'
facilities - the automatic deduction of union dues from pay packets.
The union has won a new reputation for militancy in the past few months with
two one-day strikes against rail privatisation and a decision to hold a
ballot on industrial action over the government's 1.5 per cent pay limit.
As a result of the industrial action against privatisation BR said it would
withdraw check-off, which has existed since 1965. It had been expected that
BR might change its mind, but the union executive has pre-empted this and
decided it does not want to continue with check-off as long as it can be
used as a weapon against the union.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, the union's leader, put a brave face on the move. He said:
'Leaving check-off could be a blessing in disguise, we are going to have to
re-learn some old organisational lessons.'
The union hopes that a majority of members will switch to direct debit
payments from their bank accounts, but a sizeable minority of 30 per cent to
40 per cent are expected to pay union collectors. One official said that
between 10 per cent and 25 per cent of the 68,000 members in BR were likely
to stop paying dues altogether.
The same official admitted that the union had financial problems but
stressed that the 1991 deficit was partly a result of the cost of mergers
and said the figure was substantially lower last year.
'The danger is that the income loss from ending check-off could push the
deficit back up,' he said.
Like many unions the RMT's expenditure - Pounds 10m in 1991 - was not
initially cut in line with the fall in membership income caused by large job
cuts on the railways. The union has assets of more than Pounds 12m, but most
of that is tied up in property.
</TEXT>
<XX>
