<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 93 / Lloyd's reserves rise sharply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CAPITAL base of Lloyd's of London has been dented by the insurance
market's record losses of Pounds 2.91bn, but a strong increase in the
reserves held to pay future claims mean that the deterioration has been less
marked than feared.
Overall net assets fell to Pounds 6.09bn as at the end of December 1992,
from the previous year's Pounds 6.54bn. The fall in the assets held by
Names, the individuals whose assets support the market, was compensated for
by a rise in the size of the central fund, which meets claims when Names are
unable to meet their obligations, along with an increase in other reserves.
Members' means declined from Pounds 7.30bn in 1991 to Pounds 6.38bn. These
include so-called 'funds at Lloyd's' (deposits, personal reserves and
special reserves) and other members' assets.
The net assets of the central fund increased to Pounds 1.15bn from Pounds
445m. Net assets of the Corporation of Lloyd's, which administrates and
regulates the market, fell from Pounds 263m to Pounds 252m.
Premium income - after brokerage and commission - amounted to Pounds 6.4bn
in 1992, compared with Pounds 5.01bn in 1991. An increase from Pounds 7.82bn
to Pounds 10.85bn in reinsurance premiums paid by syndicates to close their
1990 year of account also helped swell income in the premium trust funds.
Overall the US, Canadian and sterling premium trust fund plus some other
monies held by Lloyd's to meet claims grew to Pounds 16.66bn from Pounds
12.26bn.
The pre-tax loss of Pounds 2,915m was made up of losses of Pounds 1,328m
(Pounds 2,063m in 1991) from business underwritten in 1990 and a further
Pounds 1.13bn (Pounds 396m) in reserves to pay future claims on business
underwritten in earlier years.
Personal expenses of Pounds 457m (Pounds 292m) include a levy of 1.66 per
cent from each Name's 1990 premium income limit credited to the central
fund.
Provisions for current and future liabilities rose to Pounds 18.25bn from
Pounds 13.72bn.
Of the 388 syndicates trading during 1990, 115 produced a profit after
personal expenses.
The burden on Names of the special levy led to a sharp increase in market
costs to Pounds 1.43bn from Pounds 921m. Syndicate expenses fell marginally
to Pounds 671m from Pounds 673m.
Names' subscriptions fell from Pounds 55m to Pounds 51m, central fund
subscriptions from Pounds 62m to Pounds 4m, and agents' fees rose Pounds 2m
to Pounds 129m.
</TEXT>
<XX>
