<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 93 / Judge allows group action on cash machines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER and JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A JUDGE yesterday cleared the way for a mass legal action against banks and
building societies by customers claiming to have lost money through
fraudulent or 'phantom' withdrawals from automated teller machines.
In the first significant judgment in the 'phantom withdrawals' action, Judge
John Hicks QC allowed the actions to proceed together initially.
But he made clear that judgments in cases where plaintiffs claim that bank
technology has allowed withdrawals from their accounts even though they had
not disclosed their personal identification numbers to others would
eventually be made individually in the county courts.
The judge also rejected as 'misconceived' an attempt to force the
organisations involved - Barclays, Midland, Lloyds, TSB and Nationwide
Building Society - to write to all customers telling them of the legal case
and that they could join the action.
The decision extends the practice of allowing mass actions in the civil
courts. Mass actions have been common in cases involving disasters or the
side-effects of drugs such as Thalidomide, where there is a single cause
behind the complaints.
This is thought to be the first occasion a mass action has been allowed when
there are several different causes. In this case, there are differences in
the cash machine systems operated by the banks.
The test case involves nine customers claiming the return of a total of
between Pounds 15,000 and Pounds 20,000. The lead case involves Mr and Mrs
James McConville, from St Helens, Merseyside, who say they lost Pounds 400
after their cash card was stolen.
Following the judgment Barclays Bank said that it was to test the use of
cameras at six machine sites. The bank said this would aid its efforts to
prevent card fraud by allowing it to identify those carrying out fraudulent
withdrawals.
J. Keith Park, the solicitors co-ordinating the group action, said the
judgment was a victory because it would allow legal costs to be spread, and
give individual claimants the confidence to pursue actions against large
banks and societies.
The solicitors expect a further 30 customers and at least six further
defendants - NatWest, Royal Bank of Scotland, Abbey National, Halifax and
Woolwich Building Societies and Western Trust and Savings Bank - to become
involved in the action.
The judge said the plaintiffs could use 'any means properly open to them' to
encourage other bank customers with complaints about withdrawals to join the
action.
Mr Nick Davis, of J. Keith Park, said the firm had received about 1,000
inquiries from people claiming to have lost amounts from Pounds 40 to Pounds
9,000. National Westminster Bank is raising charges to retailers for which
it processes credit and debit card transactions. The rise - averaging 7 per
cent for credit cards and 9 per cent for debit cards - follows similar rises
by other banks.
The bank said it was offering to waive the increases to retailers who hired
machines to check transactions for fraud electronically.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>National Westminster Bank.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6021 National Commercial Banks.
    P6141 Personal Credit Institutions.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
    COSTS  Service costs &amp; Service prices.
