<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 93 / Women lose out over 'networking'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEN ARE seven times more likely than women to get a job by using personal
contacts, says a survey of redundant executives.
InterExec, the employment consultancy which carried out the survey, said
women had fewer female contemporaries at senior levels in business and find
it difficult to approach men to gain information about job opportunities.
The consultancy found that over the past 12 months, out of 500 redundant
executives who had been earning more than Pounds 30,000 a year, 70 per cent
of men obtained jobs by 'networking', while only 10 per cent of women got
jobs using the technique.
Mr Nick Hawkins, InterExec's chairman, said senior women were more reliant
on job advertisements and professional help than men.
Women were losing out because 63 per cent of top jobs were not advertised.
The Industrial Society said the results might indicate that women faced
discrimination when they attempted to network, and not that they were
failing to usecontacts.
Ms Jo Gardiner, Industrial Society national campaigns leader, said she
thought it unlikely that women were reluctant to contact men about job
opportunities because of a possible misunderstanding. 'The senior women I
know take a professional approach and have the courage of their convictions
 -that's how they've got where they are.'
She said women lacked the 'old boy' contacts that men had, and that was why
concerted efforts had been made by women in, for example, the City, law and
advertising, to set up networks. The Industrial Society's own network for
junior- and middle-level women in all sectors - the Pepperell network - was
launched in October and has about 1,000 members.
</TEXT>
