<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 93 / LDP tries to restore calm as Hata rebels quit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S ruling Liberal Democratic party split yesterday when Mr Tsutomu
Hata, the leader of a rebel faction, and 43 other MPs handed in their
resignations in preparation for the launch of a new political party today.
The heads of the LDP's remaining five factions held a crisis meeting in an
attempt to stabilise the party, which is in danger of losing further members
ahead of a general election called for July 18.
LDP officials conceded that the party could lose power, which it has held
since 1955, while the Social Democratic party, formerly known as the Japan
Socialist Party, believes it could rule the country in a coalition with the
Hata rebels.
Japanese foreign policy would be reviewed if the LDP lost the election, but
Mr Sadao Yamahana, the SDP chairman, yesterday told the departing US
ambassador to Japan, Mr Michael Armacost, that a socialist-led government
would still put special emphasis on the relationship with Washington.
'Whatever happens, I want to assure you that there will be no change
regarding the high importance we accord to Japan's relationship with the
US,' Mr Yamahana told Mr Armacost, who is soon to be replaced by Mr Walter
Mondale, the former US vice-president.
The SDP has traditionally opposed a US-Japan Security Treaty signed in 1951,
and the party also objected to the participation of Japanese military
personnel participating in the UN peacekeeping operation in Cambodia,
essentially because it wants the military to be disbanded.
While the LDP may be in danger of defeat, no clear pattern has emerged from
an early rush of opinion polls. A poll by the Mainichi Shimbun, a national
newspaper, of 1,000 eligible voters found that 79 per cent supported Mr
Hata's defection from the LDP, but only 9 per cent would vote for his party.
After handing in his resignation yesterday, Mr Hata said his group could not
turn back after having voted in favour of a no-confidence motion against Mr
Kiichi Miyazawa, the prime minister, on Friday night. 'Japanese politics has
already entered a new phase,' he said.
The meeting of faction heads from the LDP, which controls 232 members of the
present 476-strong lower house, resolved to put aside factional differences
for this election in an attempt to secure a parliamentary majority. Mr
Michio Watanabe, head of one faction, said the party should be able to work
in a new parliament with some of the pro-reform rebels who resigned
yesterday: 'These people are not socialists or communists - basically they
believe in the same things we do.'
