<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 93 / France confirms sell-off timetable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French government yesterday confirmed that it planned to start its
privatisation programme in early September and announced that it might sell
minority stakes in a number of state-controlled companies before the
full-scale sales got under way.
Mr Edmond Alphandery, economy minister, said after a parliamentary meeting
that he planned to float between three and six companies in the first round
of privatisations. These sales, he said, would start in the final months of
1993 but would continue in 1994.
France's new centre-right government, which needs capital to reduce the
budget deficit, recently unveiled plans for a radical privatisation drive
involving up to 21 companies. The candidates for sale include Banque
Nationale de Paris, the Renault motor group, the Rhone-Poulenc chemicals
concern and Air France.
The value of the privatisations has been estimated by analysts at between
FFr280bn and FFr360bn (Pounds 33.2bn-Pounds 42.6bn). The partial
privatisation programme before September would involve selling minority
holdings in other public sector concerns along the lines of this month's
flotation of a 35 per cent stake in the Credit Local de France banking
group. Mr Alphandery said he planned to raise around FFr40bn from
privatisations before the end of this year.
