<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 93 / UK is living beyond its means, warns Bank governor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Robin Leigh-Pemberton, the outgoing governor of the Bank of England,
yesterday warned that Britain, like other countries, was living beyond its
means and had to take action to cut its fiscal deficit, writes Peter Norman.
In an interview, Mr Leigh-Pemberton told the Financial Times that inflation
worldwide was now largely under control.
'So it would be very sad if, having almost defeated inflation, the world
drifted into an era of fiscal deficits, which reflect not so much cyclical
problems as structural elements which suggest that the industrial countries
are living beyond their means,' he said.
Britain was one such country where 'welfare payments and benefit systems are
so expensive that they are probably beyond the normal annual revenue tax
base', he said.
Mr Leigh-Pemberton said he had no quarrel with Mr Norman Lamont's March
Budget, which set out a series of tax increases to reduce the deficit but
largely postponed their implementation for at least a year.
However, he stressed that Britain had to 'get back on course to balancing
the budget over the medium term'.
Interview, Page 20
