<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / MPs hear of missing Gulf war equipment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AMMUNITION and other military supplies shipped out for British troops in the
Gulf may have been sold off by profiteers, the Commons public accounts
committee heard yesterday.
However, Dr Malcolm McIntosh, chief of defence procurement, said he would be
'very surprised' if large high technology equipment had found its way on to
the black market.
He was referring to 80 containers of supplies which were unaccounted for
after the 1991 Gulf war. Dr McIntosh said the loss rate, just over 1 per
cent, was 'about the commercial average'.
A recent National Audit Office report revealed that 228 metal aircraft
pallets, worth Pounds 680,000, were also lost. Dr McIntosh told the
committee these were often used to build troop shelters and were now
'probably just sitting in the sand.'
The committee's inquiry into Gulf shipments coincided with police
investigations into possible fraud in the arrangements of charter shipping
for the British military operation.
Dr McIntosh contested the NAO's estimate that the Ministry of Defence
overpaid shippers by Pounds 38m. He said the figure was unrealistically
based on rates for normal peace time activities.
The MoD believes the premium it paid for shipping supplies was 'closer to
zero', Dr McIntosh said.
He agreed, however, that brokerage fees of up to 8 per cent were excessive
and that the ministry would not normally be expected to pay more than 5 per
cent. 'That's not something we would like to see again at all.'
The reason British ships made up only 3 per cent of the vessels used was
that many were already engaged on contracts and others were com-paratively
expensive, he said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
