<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / Tories have 'very strict' record of donations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CONSERVATIVE party has kept 'very strict' records of every donation
received for at least 23 years, a former senior Tory fundraiser has
confirmed.
Sir Bryan Wyldbore-Smith, who was director of the party's board of finance
for 22 years leading up to the last general election, said he had submitted
a statement to the cross-party home affairs select committee, which is
inquiring into the funding of political parties.
Questioned on reports citing him as saying the Conservatives received Pounds
7m of funding just before the last election from foreign backers with
business and property interests in Britain, Sir Brian said: 'I would think
it was highly inaccurate.' The figure was 'on the high side'.
In yesterday's proceedings before the home affairs select committee the
Liberal Democrats called for the provision of state funding for political
parties to ensure 'fair competition' between them and to reduce their
financial dependence on sectional interests.
Mr Graham Elson, Liberal Democrat general secretary, told the committee that
the state should fund political parties on the basis of votes gained in
general elections - even if this meant financing Sinn Fein.
State funding should go hand in hand with curbs on the national expenditure
of parties in elections.
Acceptance of state funds should be conditional on a party publishing full
audited accounts showing the sources and application of all its funding.
Meanwhile, some senior Tory backbenchers added their voices to opposition
calls for stricter rules on the disclosure of political donations.
Mr Julian Critchley, Tory MP for Aldershot, said the 'sensible' thing for
the Conservative party to do would be to 'come clean' and have its accounts
published annually.
Senior Labour officials, including Mr Larry Whitty, general secretary, are
due to appear before the home affairs committee tomorrow as its inquiry into
funding con-tinues.
Sir Norman Fowler, Conservative party chairman, last night attacked Labour
over its links with the unions, saying its 'unprincipled campaign of smear
and unsubstantiated allegation' was 'a smokescreen for its own
embarrassments'.
He said at the Dulwich Conservative Association that Labour's real aim was
to force the taxpayer to fund political parties. 'State funding of political
parties . . . would be one of the least justified and most unpopular pieces
of public expenditure conceivable,' he said.
Sir Norman added: 'The real issue surrounding the funding of political
parties in this country is simple. It is the undemocratic way in which the
Labour party sells itself to the highest trade union bidder.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
