<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The Copenhagen Summit: EC cool to calls for end to arms ban
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
APPEALS to lift the Bosnian arms embargo found little sympathy among
European Community leaders and foreign ministers in Copenhagen last night.
President Alija Izetbegovic of Bosnia made an urgent plea to the EC to lift
the United Nations arms embargo so that the Bosnian Moslems could better
defend themselves against Serbs and Croats.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl later tried to win over other EC leaders to the idea
at a dinner of EC leaders, after he was reported to have received a letter
from US President Bill Clinton reiterating US sympathy for such a move.
Mr Izetbegovic, who flew to Copenhagen on the opening day of the EC summit,
renewed his often-sounded appeal on the arms embargo at a meeting with a
'troika' of EC foreign ministers. But he received no encouragement from the
'troika' - the foreign ministers of Britain, Denmark and Belgium
representing the former, present and next presidency of the EC.
Chancellor Kohl pressed his fellow EC leaders on the subject in what
diplomats described as tense and heated debate as the EC struggled with the
failure so far of its efforts to resolve the war in war in Bosnia.
Mr Kohl was reported to have run into tough opposition from countries such
as Britain and France which are worried about the safety of their troops
serving with the UN humanitarian mission in Bosnia.
Diplomats said Mr Kohl had received a letter in Copenhagen from President
Clinton reviving White House suggestions that the UN arms embargo should be
lifted so the Bosnian Moslems could defend themselves.
Mr Izetbegovic said: 'We request that the arms embargo be lifted to import a
limited quantity of defensive weapons.'
But Mr Niels Petersen, Danish foreign minister, said: 'In my view it is not
a sound idea to lift the weapons embargo; it would require a Security
Council resolution, which is not forthcoming, it would lead to more
fighting, and there would be great danger that United Nations forces would
have to be withdrawn.'
</TEXT>
