<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (30): A messiah of the movie
world - Media
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAY SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
J ARTHUR RANK AND THE BRITISH FILM INDUSTRY by Geoffrey Macnab Routledge
Pounds 30, 270 pages
THE BRITISH film industry, to the extent that it exists at all as a separate
entity, has been in a state of crisis as long as anyone can remember. Every
decade or so the sense of doom gives way to exhilaration as the Brits invade
the Oscars or a modest-budget picture unexpectedly takes off in the US
market.
Geoffrey Macnab's study shows just how consistent the pattern of boom and
bust has been and how the pursuit of the Holy Grail - the lucrative US
market - has usually stayed just that.
The resulting dilemmas have continued to exercise committees of inquiry as
well as film makers. Should the British concentrate on low-budget movies
aimed at the domestic market, or risk more lavish productions that have to
break into the US market to have any chance of recouping their costs?
There were high points. In the early 1930s there was an unprecedented period
of expansion, with 200 British films being made in 1936 alone - until the
financiers found they were being fleeced and retired hurt. But perhaps the
highest point of all, and the most extraordinary, was how the heir to a
flour fortune, because he wanted to make projectors available to Methodist
halls to spread the good word, turned for a time into the saviour - or to
some the monopolist - of the British film industry.
In nine years from 1933 to 1942 Rank created the largest integrated film
industry empire in British history, owning both the Odean and Gaumont cinema
chains and Pinewood and Denham studios.
Rank professed not to understand the medium of film and seemed concerned
with trade and profits but not exclusively so.
'He does not talk of British films in cultural or aesthetic terms. He alone
is in a position to effect a turn-around in British film's fortune because
he alone is powerful enough to trade on level terms with the Americans,'
Macnab argues.
Red Shoes may have taken Dollars 5m at the US box office but Rank still
found the US market impenetrable. The audience couldn't understand the
British accents and anyway were only good for 'class houses.'
Macnab recounts how Rank tried everything to create an integrated successful
industry. His projects included Independent Frame, the attempt to
revolutionise production methods, Independent Producers Ltd, which gave
producers money and creative freedom, the notorious Charm School and G-B
Animation, the move into cartoons. Most ended in acrimony; cartoon
characters like Corny the Crow, Ginger Nutt and Dusty the Mole did not stand
a prayer against Mickey Mouse.
Reality intervened in 1949 in the shape of a Pounds 16m overdraft and John
Davis, the hatchet-wielding accountant. J. Arthur Rank became more and more
remote from the film scene, Davis was in control and the Rank Organisation
had a different kind of film success - the Doctor films, the Carry On series
and the comedies of Norman Wisdom.
This closely focused study is a useful addition to the history of the
British cinema. More about Rank the man and the Rank the business would have
been welcome.
Geoffrey Macnab's conclusion is necessarily pessimistic. 'In hindsight, it
seems half comic, half tragic, that all Rank's efforts to set the British
industry on its feet should spawn nothing more than a photocopying company
and a leisure conglomerate. Bingo halls and casinos help prop up a company
which emerged from Methodist halls and Sunday schools.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
