<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (31): Read all about them -
Media
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By J D F JONES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PAPER TIGERS by Nicholas Coleridge Heinemann Pounds 17.95, 592 pages
PAPER TIGERS - if you are interested in newspapers - is a perfectly
readable, rather over-long collection of pieces about some of the people who
own the world's press. Nicholas Coleridge, formerly editor of Harpers and
Queen magazine and now managing director of Conde Nast in London, is an
accomplished feature writer. This book is in effect a collection of
interlinked articles about a selection of media tycoons, some of whom (not
all) have given him an interview. It is - to repeat - readable stuff; it is
a very superior form of gossip-columnery.
The choice of subjects is rather odd, and never satisfactorily explained.
There is a heavy initial emphasis on the US (no doubt for sound commercial
reasons) - the Sulzbergers of the New York Times, the Grahams of the
Washington Post, Otis Chandler of the Los Angeles Times, of course, but does
the non-American reader care so very much about Dean Singleton in Texas or
Jim Cox Kennedy in Atlanta?
There is an interesting chapter on the three media families of India; a
double-bite at the (uninterviewed) Warwick Fairfax, who caused such disaster
in Australia; a non-piece about the absent Robert Hersant of Le Figaro; a
section on Sally Aw Sian in Hong Kong and the mysterious and sinister
Kamphol in Thailand; an absurd and unilluminating inclusion of Asil Nadir in
Turkey; and a misguided attempt to portray the Aga Khan as a significant
newspaper tycoon on the basis of his East African operation.
Then there is the real meat of the book - Conrad Black, Rupert Murdoch, Lord
Rothermere, Lord Stevens, Tony O'Reilly, all of whom make an excellent but
deeply unsatisfying read; Robert Maxwell is not attempted seriously, which
makes sense because he would need an obituary. These chapters might interest
the European reader. (Be it noted, again, that the selection is absurdly
arbitrary: no Thomson, no Italian or German, no Japanese, no Arab, no South
African or South American.)
So what does Coleridge have to say of his chosen handful? Not very much
beyond the tittle-tattle of their lives. He is interesting on the underlying
differences between British and US papers - the UK's distinction between
quality and popular national papers as against the importance in America of
very high penetration by monopolist local newspapers (which raises the
associated issue of increasingly precise targeting of ever-smaller - and
therefore more parochial? - district or regional markets.)
He argues that proprietors are still all-powerful, though fewer in number,
and by implication greater in clout. He discusses this point with a few of
them and is promised that he need not worry. When challenged by public
perceptions, Coleridge is usually reassured by his interviewee. He admits,
for example, that Murdoch has many critics, but concludes that: 'The culture
of his newspapers, particularly the tabloids, may indeed be brutal and
chauvinistic and downmarket, but that is not quite the same thing as
invariably moving the paper downmarket.'
Conrad Black of the Telegraph, Sydney Morning Herald, Jerusalem Post and
North Bay Nugget comes out of this book as the most interesting of the
UK-oriented tigers, perhaps because he is the least known and also the big
mover at present. Lord Rothermere of the Mail, the Standard and the Spilsby
and Skegness Target is the most cuddly ('He is probably the only one who
devotes any time to introspection'). Rupert Murdoch - who owns almost
everything else - turns on the charm and Coleridge laps it up.
This is, I hope it is clear, an unashamedly soft-centered portrait of
various Streets of Shame. My objection is that there is no attempt to
report, let alone analyse, the business operations of these people. Mr
Coleridge may modestly feel that he is unqualified to attempt the task, but
the snag is that the important part of the story is indeed their business
deals.
It is all very well to know that Murdoch denies being a 'born again'
Christian (merely 'practising') or that Rothermere has a Korean lady
companion, but the heart of the book should be something different: how, for
instance, did Murdoch manage to roll over his debt burden at a moment when
he faced disaster? What was the breakthrough point for the Mail on Sunday?
In such terms, Paper Tigers is not a serious book - and, fair enough, it
probably was not intended to be.
There is a curious omission. The FT does not figure in these pages -
surprising, since we surely have a role in the world more influential than
Mr Nadir's Ekonomik Bulteno. Is it because we are not 'controlled' by a
single proprietor, whatever that means? I would have thought that the
effective control of a one-armed polo-playing peer - whom, in 30 years as an
FT journalist I have never seen, nor expected to - would have been the stuff
of Mr Coleridge's dreams. It goes to show that the Cowdray family has a
genius for keeping out of the gossip columns.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
