<PROFILE>_AN-DFVCUAHFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930622
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (29): The packaging of
pleasure - Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR GOD, COUNTRY AND COCA-COLA by Mark Pendergrast Charles
Scribner's/Maxwell Macmillan International Dollars 27.50, 556pp
WHO WOULD have ever believed that a fizzy, sugary water could become the
world's most ubiquitous consumer product and turn the company that makes it
into a gold mine? That is the question that underlies Mark Pendergrast's
book.
His answer, like authors before him, is that Coca-Cola's leaders have been
shrewder than most for seeing the power of innovative, often ground-breaking
advertising to hype this soft drink to its exalted status of world brand.
But what distinguishes Pendergrast's account is that it is painstakingly
well-researched and, for the most part, cleverly written. The book has
touched off some controversy because of Pendergrast's claim that he
inadvertently found the original Coca-Cola formula, an invention of Georgia
pharmacist John Pemberton in the 1880s. Given that the formula is one of the
world's best-kept commercial secrets, Pendergrast's discovery of the formula
in an old file in the company's own library seems an extraordinary coup. The
company, naturally, suggests that the recipe he found is not genuine.
The book is full of telling anecdotes about Coke's inventor and early
leaders, Asa Candler and Robert Woodruff. It seems that Pemberton concocted
the drink, with a small amount of cocaine and a greater dose of caffeine,
largely as a remedy for his morphine habit. Candler, a miserly Atlanta
entrepreneur, was the first to see the potential of what was then just a
patent medicine that gave a lift to the consumer and relieved Candler's own
headaches. By 1888, he acquired the rights to it, not entirely honestly,
from the many parties to whom these were dispersed by Pemberton. He quickly
transformed the medicine into a popular soft drink. But its popularity soon
had a price. Public campaigns against products with cocaine forced Candler
to take the kick out of the drink by 1903.
Robert Woodruff, a crackerjack salesman and Coca-Cola's leader until the
early 1980s, is the man who made it a worldwide phenomenon. In his greatest
move, Woodruff manoeuvered to obtain Washington's blessing to manufacture
Coke around the globe for American soldiers during the second world war,
thus laying the groundwork for Coke's empire today.
But the book is lamentably shorter on insightful details about Coca-Cola's
current chairman, Roberto Goizueta, the Cuban-born chemical engineer who
took over in 1981. He shares the same limitless vision for Coke as his
predecessors; he once mused: 'Perhaps coming years will see a time when
consumers will have Coca-Cola taps in their homes.'
Goizueta was responsible for the biggest gaff in the company's history, the
attempt in the mid-1980s to alter Coke's formula. Yet Goizueta emerged
unscathed from the New Coke disaster, perhaps not least because he had
enlivened the company's performance for its shareholders.
The book is not all dinner party fodder and praise for Coke. It evenhandedly
reveals the seamier episodes of the company's history, including its
accommodation to Hitler, apartheid and Guatemalan death squads as well as
its shoddy treatment of its migrant workers. It is worth reading for those
who want a history, in Pendergrast's words, of the 'modern American attempt
to package pleasure.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-1717</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DFVCUAHEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930622
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (28): Bench marks -
Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STRATEGIC BENCHMARKING by Gregory Watson John Wiley Dollars 29.95 pages
BENCHMARKING is one of those management practices which has taken time to
take root on both sides of the Atlantic. US companies were systematically
studying, and learning from, the processes of outstanding competitors, and
even non-competitors, in the early and mid-1980s. But only in the current
decade has this quality improvement technique become a hot topic for the
consultants.
One reason is that pundits initially likened benchmarking to 'industrial
espionage', maintaining that the concept of sharing information and
experiences was contrary to the principles of the free market.
Watson argues persuasively that there need be no conflict, though he betrays
a somewhat evangelistic streak when describing benchmarking as part of a
coherent (American) national challenge for continuous productivity
improvement. 'There is a more efficient use of 'society's resources' than
requiring every company to invest in relearning the lessons of the
marketplace.'
As vice president, Quality, of the Office Documents Division of the Xerox
Corporation - the company widely credited with inventing benchmarking - the
author is at his best discussing its implementation as a business process
improvement strategy rather than philosophising.
It hammers home the important point that exceptional performance is achieved
not just by measuring other people's results but by applying the lessons (or
identifying what he calls 'process enablers'). If sometimes a shade
repetitive the book is full of useful practical observations.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-1718</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DFVCUAHDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930622
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (27): A computing world
beyond science fiction - Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ST GEORGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VISIONS OF THE FUTURE: ART, TECHNOLOGY AND COMPUTING IN THE TWENTY-FIRST
CENTURY edited by Clifford A. Pickover Science Reviews, 212 pages
THE JOURNAL Popular Mechanics in 1949 tentatively predicted 'computers in
the future may have only 1,000 vacuum tubes and perhaps only weigh 1.5
tons.' Now Visions of the Future, a catholic congregation of essays on
technology and computing over the next decade, is suggesting that we may
soon have computers floating in our bloodstream. They are already in the
palm of our hand.
The book's faults are understandable: it spreads itself thinly over
Artificial Intelligence, electronic storytelling, weather mapping, Virtual
Reality and even the Global Enneper-Weierstrauss representation for Minimal
Surfaces. This loose gathering of tentative technology should be balanced by
reading an account of changes in computing such as Technology 2001: The
Future of Computing and Communications (MIT Press, 1991).
However, Visions of the Future maps out a variety of roles for computer
technologies and applications, ranging from golf to traffic control via
molecular biology and prehistory. Amid this diversity, three unifying themes
emerge. The first is the interdisciplinary nature of the new technology.
Computing as a technical process may be electronic, but as a human procedure
it is eclectic. Here are essays on visualising numbers, on teaching writing
to groups of students, and on a model career as a computer sculptor.
The second theme is the matter of how changes in computer design will affect
how we communicate with each other over the next 20 years. Electronic mail
and computer conferencing are still teenagers at IBM, but the pace of change
itself will quicken as computer hardware improves.
Here, Davis Albert Foulger of IBM's TJ Watson Research Center at Yorktown
Heights has a fascinating essay on computer communication which runs from
Marshall McLuhan through Star Trek. He presents a three-dimensional model
media space, showing the relations between types of communication: film, TV,
animation, letters, telephone. Computer communications, being so adaptable,
create links between other media to produce programmes of text, pictures,
voiceovers and direct contact between users, what Foulger calls
'voice-into-text concurrent interaction.'
The third theme should be a comfort: as computers advance, humans can feel
more satisfied with their own brains. Granted, computers now surpass us in
technical logical skills; rational thinking, around 100,000 years old, is a
still relatively new, and serious competition arrived only with the
computer. But human survival (and that of our ancestors) has for millions of
years depended on skills which computers cannot perform: seeing and moving
in the physical world. A computer which can model fractal geometry and
Mandelbrot Sets at millions of calculations per second still cannot
recognise itself in a mirror.
Computers can search a database, but only when instructed to look for data
or patterns of data already present. The success of books as forms of
information storage - robust, browsable, accessible, - has yet to be
surpassed. The look and feel of books are better for half-remembered
information, that paragraph at the foot of a left-hand page beginning with a
part-remembered line, or that name rhyming with 'orange'.
Behind the 20 essays in Visions of The Future lies an unexpressed question.
If, as some claim, human identity (rather than personal identity) can be
reduced to the nucleic acids DNA and RNA, in what sense can computers -
reduced to strings of programmes - be said to have identity? The answer
hangs on the difference between carbon-based and silicon-based units.
</TEXT>
