<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (24): The never-ending quest
for quality - Management / Charles Batchelor on why the new BS5750 standard
is vital to commercial success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMPLEMENTING QUALITY THROUGH BS5750 (ISO 9000) by Peter Jackson and David
Ashton Kogan Page Pounds 25, 226 pages
WE MAY NOT know exactly what we mean by quality but few would argue with the
premise that is a good thing. Britain, with the poor reputation many of its
products acquired during in the 1960s and 1970s, is surely in need of it
more than most.
How can we explain, then, the controversy which has arisen over BS5750, a
quality management standard which has been adopted by some 20,000 UK
companies? (And overseas, in its international equivalent ISO9000, by
several thousand more.)
BS5750 has been criticised for being expensive, bureaucratic and not
actually guaranteeing product or service quality.
Small businesses in particular have complained that their large customers
are using BS5750 as a crude mechanism for discriminating against suppliers.
Large companies are increasingly demanding that all their suppliers meet
BS5750 even if they have previously had no complaints about the quality of
deliveries.
Part of the problem is due to the inevitable pains of moving from the
informal quality systems present in many small firms to the more formal
procedures required by BS5750. There is also no doubt that the British
Standards Institution could have done a better job of explaining the
principles behind the standard. BSI and industry are familiar with narrow,
industry-specific standards but 'horizontal' standards, covering issues such
as quality and environmental management and relevant across a broad swathe
of industry, are a relatively new idea.
Implementing Quality does not directly tackle these broader questions, being
more concerned with providing practical guidance to companies seeking to
register for BS5750. But it inevitably touches on some of the issues which
have been raised.
There is often a substantial cost involved in obtaining and maintaining
registration, but this will normally be exceeded many times by the benefits
from holding on to existing customers and winning new ones, the authors
state.
Gearing up for BS5750 can result in 'culture shock' for businesses used to
informal quality controls. The need to record business activities so that
mistakes can be traced and corrected may increase the volume of paperwork,
though not to an unacceptable degree. Increased formality has its
advantages, argue the authors, respectively a manager who has introduced
BS5750 and a consultant. Staff will be more willing to accept tighter
controls if they know they are part of a coherent quality system and not
just the result of managerial whim.
Before describing in detail how to implement BS5750, this guide begins with
a useful discussion of what is meant by quality. The conventional view is
that it represents 'the best' and by implication the most expensive. In
fact, quality should mean 'the meeting of customer requirements', whether
this is for an expensive watch which enhances the wearer's prestige and
lasts a lifetime or for an inexpensive one which keeps accurate time.
Quality, in this sense, can be achieved by the many thousands of existing
quality and service standards which have been devised over the years.
Quality systems go beyond this to ensure that the process of manufacture or
service delivery are carried out with maximum efficiency and minimum cost.
In the past quality control has consisted of weeding out faulty products at
the end of the production line. But this can be costly and in the case of
many services - a restaurant meal, legal advice - impossible to check before
the customer has discovered the fault. Quality systems, by contrast, analyse
the process by which a product is made or service delivered, identify the
correct methods and attempt to systematise them. Faulty procedures are
detected and designed out of the system.
An example quoted is of a company which had continual problems with a new
plating machine. The consultants found that each new shift was re-adjusting
the machine because operators had misunderstood their original operating
instructions. A manual setting down the correct adjustment would have
eliminated this sort of misunderstanding.
For the businessman considering registering for BS5750 this book provides a
valuable guide, clarifying the sometimes confusing detail of the standard.
When BS5750 first came to prominence, business owners asked themselves
whether they could afford to have it. Increasingly they are having to decide
whether they can afford not to have it.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
