<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (25): A door always open -
Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILF ALTMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HUMAN TOUCH by Bill Arnold and Jeanne Plas John Wiley, Dollars 22.95 272
pages
WHEN Bill Arnold became president of Centennial Medical Centre in Nashville,
Tennessee, he turned the corporate pyramid upside down by announcing an
'open door' policy.
Everyone thought it was just another management slogan - until he had his
door taken off the hinges and hung in the lobby as a monument to an outdated
leadership style.
He called it 'person-centred leadership' - a simple management philosophy
based on listening, helping people to work together, to build self-esteem
and mutual respect, and spreading decision making right through the
organisation.
He proved that allowing people to develop actually led to lower running
costs, dramatically higher sales and profits, improved cash flow and a 50
per cent reduction in staff turnover.
Centennial is the largest commercial medical centre in the US, the flagship
of the giant Hospital Corporation of America. Some 3,000 staff and 900 house
physicians run three large hospitals and seven medical office buildings,
dealing with around 116,000 'customers' and 360,000 worried/relieved
visitors a year.
Employees, or 'associates' as they became known, began to enjoy coming to
work. When other chief executives argued that running a hospital is rather
different from most large scale businesses Bill Arnold pointed out the
problems were not so different since they also involved providing
services/products and dealing with government regulations, budgeting,
management, customer satisfaction, market share and the 'bottom line'.
If person-centred management can work in a for-profit medical centre of this
size and complexity, he argues, it probably can work anywhere.
Arnold's 'hard-nosed, humanistic' principles are concerned with listening to
gripes, resolving personal frustrations, promoting honesty, an open-door
policy, encouraging new ideas, the use of brief, hand-written memos and
creating a shared vision.
How these principles were implemented, including the expected initial round
of errors, is chronicled by Bill Arnold, the doer, and by his collaborator,
Jeanne Plas, a distinguished academic who took a close interest in all
stages of the transformation.
The reason person-centred leadership took off so dramatically within this
complicated corporate environment, she suggests, 'is that it is compatible
with basic human needs. Bill insisted that his organisation had to start
from scratch. It had to get rid of some outdated dysfunctional ways of
operating and ineffective ways of thinking . . . begin with what people
need; marry those ideas to the needs of the organisation. Encourage people
to care about one another and the enterprise. Have some fun.'
It sounds deceptively simple, but The Human Touch is a remarkable account of
its effective implementation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
