<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (23): Why the Think Tanks
overflow - Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ST GEORGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TRANSFORMATION OF AMERICAN POLITICS: THE NEW WASHINGTON AND THE RISE OF
THE THINK TANKS by David M Ricci Yale Pounds 25, 310 pages
SYSTEMS OF SURVIVAL: A DIALOGUE ON THE MORAL FOUNDATIONS OF COMMERCE AND
POLITICS by Jane Jacobs Hodder &amp; Stoughton Pounds 16.99, 238 pages
DIAL 'M' for Political Theorist: Machiavelli, Madison, Mandeville, Marx,
Mill, Montaigne, Montesquieu, More; and the middle name of David M. Ricci,
who has written a stimulating academic account of the Washington Think Tank.
This amounts to a book about how ideas enter into public life as data,
speeches, or public policy research. The pluralism in Washington which makes
President Clinton appear indecisive results from the rise of non-government
lobby and public policy organisations at a time when the Washington
professional was becoming a manipulator of information rather than an
interpreter of moral or spiritual certainties.
While WASP ideals and the Eastern establishment (such as the Council on
Foreign Relations in New York) held sway in the 1970s, the thinkers emerging
from institutions like Harvard's Kennedy School simply took the train south
and plied their trade in Washington. In England, Oxford graduates became
civil servants and Cambridge graduates professional spies. In America, Ivy
League professional schools fed the equivalent of their own Washington
bureaux, pro or contra government. Bored lawyers, tired of government
contracts, had the opportunity for pro-bono work in social or political
causes to remind them why they became lawyers in the first place. There was
plenty of excess capacity: membership of the DC Bar trebled between 1973 and
1981 (to 34,000); you were more likely to be sued than mugged on the Metro.
The Think Tanks grew on this supply of expertise. The Brookings Institution
(1927), the Institute for Policy Studies (1963), the Heritage Foundation
(1973) and countless Political Action Committees provided the jobs and the
environment for informed debate adjacent to the academy and to government.
Alongside them, professional research organisations also prospered in the
1970s and 1980s; by 1981 there were 80,000 private research association
staff in Washington.
'Anyone who can raise enough money and hire the right sort of experts,' says
Ricci, 'can establish a think tank and start churning out books,
newsletters, briefing, conferences, and the like. The really acute questions
are who will pay attention to these sorts of things, if at all, and why.'
But the book fails to answer those acute questions. He interviews few people
in power, and decides not to chart specific legislative measures which flow
like pulses of energy through the Washington medium.
Ricci focuses too narrowly on Washington. After all, Messrs Bradley,
Woodward and Bernstein were to be found in the Hamptons in the 1980s, mixing
with New York media people on Long Island. He also mentions but ignores the
impact of that American institution, the Op-Ed page, a much more catholic
gathering of voices than its counterpart in the UK.
The book periodically returns to the question of 'how things get done on the
Potomac', as if Wall Street finance houses or Mid-Town public relations
agencies (the new Madison Avenue after advertising's decline in the late
1980s) have no purchase on power. Already in the mid-1980s public relations
firms in New York were retained by foreign governments to manipulate
information outside Washington - a form of privatised diplomacy.
It may be that the National Journal (January 1986) correctly identified the
150 men and women in Washington 'who made a difference', but the technique
of identifying and contacting opinion formers by direct means was part of
John Scanlon's brilliant campaign for CBS in the Westmorland Trial during
1985 in New York. In other words, Washington has no monopoly on either
influence or sophisticated information management.
This is not Hedrick Smith's gossipy, informed Washington case study, The
Power Game, because Ricci determines to deliver history rather than
information. The essence of Washington flavours books like Zbigniew
Brzezinski's 1983 Power and Principle, Stephen Hess's The Ultimate Insiders
(published by The Brookings Institute, 1986) or even Garry Wills's Reagan's
America: Innocents At Home (1987). Read these, alongside Walter Isaacson's
superb recent biography of Kissinger, for full Washington exposure.
The strengths of Ricci's book lie in his history and his allusiveness. He
holds Francis Bacon responsible, in The New Atlantis (1624) for creating the
idea of a clearing house for the wise, an apolitical symposium of ideas
called Salomon's House. The early Constitutional notion of an equilibrium of
opinions found expression in the 1960s and 1970s when the expertise, the
marketing and the need for multiplied opinions led to the formation and
growth of the Think Tank.
Ricci writes excellently on the growth and scientification of American
higher education since 1865, on the arrival of what he calls Big Government
after the New Deal, on the decline of WASP ideals and the rise of a cultural
and political pluralism, and on the increasing privatisation of government
such that Jimmy Carter said in 1978: 'Government cannot solve our problems .
. . eliminate poverty, or provide a bountiful economy, or reduce inflation,
or save our cities.'
Alongside Ricci's detailed polemic, Systems of Survival: A Dialogue on the
Moral Foundations of Commerce and Politics by Jane Jacobs is a difficult,
coded dinner-table symposium rather like Castiglione's Book of the Courtier
or one of Thomas Love Peacock's novels. Jacobs maintains that human systems
devolve into Commercial or Guardian syndromes, the former relying on
contractual and collaborative patterns of behaviour, the latter on hierarchy
and individuality. Fundamental questions emerge, but the format drains them
of seriousness: the diners interrupt each other with 'This is a mite
far-fetched' or 'Stop right there. I've heard about leveraged buyouts - who
hasn't - but I don't understand them.'
Legal and social theorists such as Judith Schklar or Robert Nozick or Martha
Nussbaum patrol the same beat, but have the advantage of citing the sources.
Jacobs's notes should be more integrated into the text, not excised from it.
The range of reference is both wide and enthusiastic: from Stephen Jay
Gould's 'co-opted epiphenomena' back to Machiavelli the political theorist.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
