<DATE>930622
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (22): Of Mammon versus
Bacchus - Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TIME AND MONEY: THE MAKING OF CONSUMER CULTURE by Gary Cross Routledge
Pounds 13.99, 294 pages
THE RISE AND FALL OF MASS MARKETING edited by Richard S Tedlow and Geoffrey
Jones Routledge Pounds 35, 239 pages
SOMEWHERE in the recent past humanity decided it would forgo the pleasures
of the sloth in order to enjoy those of the international computer salesman,
a decision not entirely to the liking of all those not party to its making.
Time and Money is about that decision, how in the last two centuries we have
reached the point where increased consumption, rather than increased
leisure, has become the central goal of economic activity. Cross has written
a worthy if somewhat academically dry text which details the pros and cons
of the debate.
There are some grimly entertaining moments, not the least being those where
it is evident that some of the earliest feminists unwittingly colluded in a
version of reinforced self-enslavement. Their arguments that they should be
granted as much right to a full working week in abysmal factories as men now
seem a trifle absurd, rather like pleading to endure more discomfort to
prove equality. But perhaps that itself was progress?
In the end though the book ducks the real issue - how, in a complex and
increasingly global economy, can the temptations of Mammon be balanced
against the seductions of Bacchus, without being excessively tied to either?
If Time and Money is slightly disappointing, then The Rise and Fall of Mass
Marketing is a suitable candidate for investigation by the Advertising
Standards Authority; the title promises much but the cupboard sometimes
seems a little bare.
The 11 essays - on topics as varied as the marketing of motor cars in the UK
before 1950 and wheat marketing since 1945 - are essentially retrospectives,
attempts to grapple with the history of certain aspects of marketing rather
than bring light to bear on contemporary marketing problems by using past
experience.
One of the central problems for marketing is its lack of a stable,
universally agreed definition. 'Is one discussing advertising, brand
building, warehousing, transportation, pricing, consumer research, or a
combination of the above?' ask the editors in their introduction.
They have opted for most of the contributors to concentrate on issues of
distribution, and some of the pieces - such as Geoffrey Tweedale's essay on
the development of mass marketing of computers - are unexpectedly absorbing.
But the overall use of the volume is very classroom bound, though as an
attempt to create an academic credibility for marketing - certainly one of
the more surprising growth areas in the UK's new polyversities - the book as
a whole makes advances.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-1724</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DFVCUAG7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930622
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (21): The very nuts and
bolts of change - Management / Christopher Lorenz on the management world's
most fashionable fad, process re-engineering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER LORENZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF YOU have just parachuted from Mars, or flown in from a six-month sojourn
in the Seychelles, the term 'process re-engineering' may conjure up nothing
more than the pipework of a chemical plant, or something equally obscure.
If, on the other hand, you have skimmed the occasional business newspaper or
magazine, you will know that 're-engineering' promises some sort of
revolution, and has burst with a vengeance on to the management scene since
Christmas. It has hit America especially hard, becoming the most instant
fashion since 'excellence' a decade ago.
If you have been reading more carefully, you will know that the reason for
the craze is that re-engineering promises productivity miracles in virtually
every industry through the complete redesign of white-collar 'business
processes.'
The last fad to grip the executive world, total quality management, took as
many years to gather momentum as it does, through 'continuous improvement,'
to accumulate dramatic pay-offs in cost, quality, and productivity. In
contrast, re-engineering promises in just a year or two to squeeze at least
ten-fold the time taken to complete many processes. This is achieved by
replacing their traditionally fragmented, poorly connected processes, which
operate within narrow, separate and steeply hierarchical 'functional'
departments.
In their place, a growing canon of US and European companies has installed
single processes which span their organisations from side to side. A typical
one will embrace sales, ordering, installation, billing and cash collection
in one single stream of activity undertaken by multi-disciplinary teams.
Another will link the design, development, engineering and production of new
products and services.
Beneath the detail, the most revolutionary aspect of re-engineering is that
it challenges a prime principle on which 20th century organisations have
been based: the maxims of 'Taylorism' (after Frederick Taylor) and 'Fordism'
(after Henry Ford), that work should be broken into narrow, specialised
activities and departments so that it can be supervised and controlled.
It is the impact of re-engineering on the social and authority structures of
organisations which makes it so difficult to achieve. It requires not only
the redesign of the 'hard' elements of an enterprise - the processes
themselves, and the systems which 'enable' them - but also considerable
change in the organisation's 'soft' aspects: its people, their skills,
behaviour, values and culture.
With so much at stake - plus hefty publishing royalties and consulting fees
 -it is not surprising that the past six months have seen a flood of books
on the subject.
The most hyped by far is Re-engineering the Corporation, by Michael Hammer
and James Champy (Nicholas Brealey Pounds 16.99, 223 pages). These two
consultants have done more to define the 'hard' side of re-engineering than
anyone else; Hammer runs his own firm, while Champy heads CSC Index.
The virtue of their book is its brevity, readibility and - for the most part
 -clarity. It certainly explains the nuts and bolts of re-engineering and
illustrates them well with packaged case studies. But it suffers from
several drawbacks. Most important are its lack of detail on several key
issues and its inconsistent approach to the cultural changes which are
needed if re-engineering is not to run into a brick wall, or be undermined.
Having declared in a surprising slip on page three that 'business
re-engineering doesn't try to change the behaviour of American workers and
managers,' by chapter four Hammer and Champy are exemplifying the very
opposite: the vast changes in attitudes, values and behaviour that must be
associated with re-engineering.
They are also inconsistent about whether they think behavioural and cultural
change - 'empowerment,' teamwork and so on - are an automatic result of the
re-engineering of business processes, or whether such 'soft' change needs to
be launched in parallel or even beforehand. Controversially, much of the
book suggests that soft follows hard automatically, yet at Bell Atlantic,
one of their prime case study companies, a culture change programme was
launched two years ahead of re-engineering. This is not explained in the
book.
Surprisingly in view of its subtitle, which focuses on information
technology, Thomas Davenport's Process Innovation (HBS Press/McGraw Hill
Pounds 26.95, 337 pages) does a better but less readable job of relating all
the hard and soft elements of re-engineering to each other. This is partly
because Davenport made his book 50 per cent longer, but also because he sees
re-engineering as only part of his universe, rather than its core.
Davenport, a partner at Ernst and Young, underlines that re-engineering is
only part of what has to be done when processes are changed radically.
Refreshingly, he uses the term to refer purely to the actual design of the
new processes. Far tougher and more 'wrenching,' he rightly says, are the
human and organisational dimensions of change. He is also clear that
behaviour and culture changes are necessary bedfellows of re-engineering,
rather than its automatic progeny. For companies setting out on the
re-engineering trail, this is a critical distinction.
In a different and equally useful sense, Business Process Re-engineering
(John Wiley Pounds 24.95, 241 pages) by Henry J Johansson and three other
consultants from Coopers and Lybrand, also takes a refreshingly broad
approach. For one thing, it is not entirely American. For another, its USP
is to make re-engineering less inward-looking by setting it in the context
of marketing and business strategy.
Like others, Johansson and Co distinguish between two types of
re-engineering: first, that which creates dramatic cost, time and
productivity improvements in rather narrow business processes, such as Dun
and Bradstreet's establishment of credit-rating contracts; second, that
which helps a company achieve parity, or 'best in class,' in an entire
'core' process, such as the design-to-delivery cycle within AT&amp;T.
But the Coopers team also adds a third type: the occasional process
revolution which enables a company to leapfrog way ahead of its rivals by
changing the rules of an entire market or industry. Wal-Mart re-engineered
its 'supply chain' by replacing its own warehouses and distribution centres
with point of sale systems linked instantly through to key suppliers. As a
result it could offer its retail customers constantly refilled shelves of
branded products at considerably cut prices. Its competitors reeled.
Gluttons for jargon like all consultants, the Coopers team calls this the
achievement of a strategic 'BreakPoint.' This is defined as when market
share 'moves disproportionately upward' as a result of customers perceiving
a dramatic improvement in cost, quality, service or lead time, or in all
four.
Compared with the first three books, Re-engineering Your Business (McGraw
Hill Pounds 21.95, 247 pages) by Daniel Morris and Joel Brandon, will be
more of a minority taste. It is far drier and much more of a hands-on guide
to particular methods of re-engineering. But it also gives some useful
general reminders: for instance, that processes should not be re-engineered
in an internal vacuum, but only after the competitive advantage to be
achieved in each situation has been analysed.
Not really a book, but more of a study - and much more expensive - is one of
the first publications to appear last winter on the subject, Business
Re-engineering, by Peter Bartram (Business Intelligence, tel: 081-544-1830.
Pounds 395, 296 pages). Though some of its contents have been outdated, it
still provides a very welcome, plain person's guide to the field. It is
unusually rich in case studies, especially of companies in Britain. It also
contains a useful list of consultants in the field.
</TEXT>
