</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (17): Nintendo's power play
 -Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GAME OVER: HOW NINTENDO ZAPPED AN AMERICAN INDUSTRY, CAPTURED YOUR DOLLARS,
AND ENSLAVED YOUR CHILDREN by David Sheff Random House, Dollars 25 480 pages
DURING 1990 the unthinkable happened. For the first time 'Q' ratings in the
US, derived from surveys to indicate the popularity of politicians, film
stars and other public figures, showed that Super Mario, Nintendo's
electronic game mascot, was more recognised by American children than Mickey
Mouse.
'The idea that Mario had become more popular than Mickey was to some a
travesty that signaled the next phase of the Japanese invasion,' writes
California-based author David Sheff.
Sheff's book, researched over two years on the basis of interviews with
Nintendo executives and its rivals, charts the rise and rise of the Japanese
electronic games company through the late 1980s. In the process it provides
a vivid but critical insight into the Kyoto-based company and its autocratic
founder, Hiroshi Yamauchi.
This is not a video games technical manual but an eminently readable
business book which explains how, after a rocky start, Nintendo came to
dominate a multi-billion-dollar industry in less than a decade. As many
parents know, Nintendo is a force to be reckoned with. But anyone who has
trouble taking seriously a company which built its success around an
electronic cartoon character - a Brooklyn plumber supercharged with
mushrooms who battles bomb-hurling mice, waltzing cacti and turtles - need
only read some of the statistics in the first chapter.
Nintendo is an astonishing success. By the end of the 1980s, just five years
after the launch of the first Super Mario game, profits earned from its
video games and the Nintendo Entertainment System hardware had transformed
it into one of the world's most profitable companies. By 1991 it had
replaced Toyota as Japan's most successful company.
In 1991 the company earned about Dollars 1.5m for each of its 4,000
worldwide employees. Sony, with 10 times as many employees, earned Dollars
400m less. Last year Nintendo's pre-tax profits topped Dollars 1bn on sales
of Dollars 5.75bn. There are as many Nintendo machines in the world - 50m to
60m - as personal computers. About a third of all US and Japanese homes now
have a Nintendo-games playing machine. How has this been achieved?
The key, argues Sheff, is that 'Nintendo had predicated its entire strategy
on the control of both hardware and software.' Nintendo has kept tight
control over the games cartridges, and extracting royalties for each of the
170m cartridges sold last year. In addition, Nintendo has pursued its
strategy with single-minded determination, taking whatever action necessary
to secure and maintain its dominant market position. As Sheff points out
this has included a 'scorched earth' policy towards competitors, exclusive
pacts with game developers and chip manufacturers, and a readiness to do
battle with governments on three continents.
Nevertheless, Sheff argues that Nintendo made a serious mistake when it
delayed releasing a more advanced 16-bit machine - a lapse which allowed
Sega, its arch rival, to secure a foothold in the market.
Sheff, like his Nintendo-addicted son, is a video games fan, but his study
is far from uncritical. If the book has a weakness it is when it looks to
the future. Otherwise this book explains why Nintendo and video games are
more than just kids' stuff.
</TEXT>
